Last year I learned how to ask for help. I struggled with mental health problems and took on tasks that were beyond my individual scope. I’ve always tried to be independent, and in 2022 I felt the consequences of that. It was time to change. 

These photos represent many of the people (and animals) who helped me, based on the order I came across the photos on my phone. I am grateful to my mom and sister @immollyicookthings , to @natebender10 for his help making @footprintsrunning a real thing, to @paige.on.purpose for supporting all my frantic shit, to @nnormal_official for letting me join their amazing launch, to @trailboundsketches and @jakeblackandwhite for their constant patience and mentorship, to my therapist for helping me move forward, to so many other people for their help. The generosity of the good people in my life shows me how to do good for other people in turn. 

Here’s to a 2023 as challenging and rewarding as 2022! Please help me figure out how to do that!

My friend @brodyleven took me skiing this week. I met him in 2017 for a climbing trip in Moab and right away I knew he was someone I wanted to spend more time with. Every time I see him, Brody makes me feel at ease and interesting, which speaks to his humility. He also will hear out my ideas and give me honest feedback, the kind of response that helps make those ideas better. Brody is also a great athlete who has done more than most to bring climate action and an uphill ethos into the outdoor world. I’m lucky to have him as my friend.

When I started @footprintsrunning I didn’t know if our camps would work at all. I hoped they would, but sometimes it’s safer to think about the task at hand than the big picture. But 3 years later we’ve found our stride (ha) and we’re hosting two camps in the US and one in Australia! I’m constantly amazed at what our runners have helped us accomplish. 

Last night we announced the Australia camp and I’m just so proud of our team. We’ve partnered with @wild.allies to organize the event in their proven way, using much of the materials and lessons we’ve learned over the years at our US camps. It’s an exciting new chapter for Footprints, and it’s the style I dream of for the future: who else can we empower to put on climate action events that I couldn’t do? Women’s camps? Camps for people of color? Indigenous leadership camps? If Footprints is truly successful, I’ll get out of the way and follow those who have been marginalized but who are actually capable of helping our world find a sustainable future. 

If you’re in Victoria, Australia, check out the Footprints camp there this April. If not, follow along anyway: we’re making climate action possible for all people everywhere. 

#runfootprints

Transferring to the @universityofutah was a nightmare, but it was made worth it by getting to work with Dr. Marc Calaf. I reached out to him last year asking about research opportunities, and he has gone out of his way to welcome me to his lab, introduce me to great people, support my work, and make me feel at home in every way. He’s also a badass outdoor athlete from Catalunya. I’m really grateful to get to learn from him. 

Today, after months of prep and a few weeks of delay, we finally got my weather station on the roof. We’re going to be measuring atmospheric conditions near a rooftop solar array to study how the PV panels affect - and are affected by - the conditions around them. The end goal is to help these systems be more cost effective and efficient than ever. It’s a fun combo of engineering and atmospheric science - exactly what I want to learn about.

My training philosophy has changed over the years. For a long time I was willing to do whatever it took to be successful; I thought if I did the right training and was perfectly fit (whatever THAT means), then I’d be more capable of doing what I loved: running in the mountains. I also felt a compulsion to race well b/c I wanted to please my sponsors. 

This was the wrong attitude. I don’t like data that much, and I was trying to do a kind of training that benefits from quantification without committing to the quantification. I wasn’t inspired by that kind of training and I didn’t communicate to my coach how I felt, so he never could help the way he wanted. Mostly, I forgot to do what I loved: run in wild places for the simple joy of it. 

This first photo shows my girlfriend @paige.on.purpose helping me at @javelinajundred last fall - this underscores the sacrifices the people around me make to help me succeed. How can I use my running to help others succeed? It has to start with me remembering what I love about running and prioritizing that. These days, I wear a watch on less than half my runs, and I record my training in a journal when I remember. I tell myself: if the training I like to do doesn’t prepare me for the race, then I’ve chosen the wrong race. I certainly have a method to my training (learned from @jasonkoop ), but I apply that method on a near-daily basis. How do I feel today? Am I tired or motivated? Usually when I don’t want to run, I know I’m too tired and I take a break. I’ll turn around if I’m not having fun. I rest more and play more. 

I am far from the best at training, but I work hard and I’ve had more fun running in the last three years than in many before that. And it seems to be working anyway. Don’t forget WHY you do the things you love, and what you love about them. 

Photos from Javelina by @nickmdanielson

We’ve changed the structure to help people with their climate projects more directly and for a longer time, providing resources and connections that can help runners become climate leaders in their own communities. #ad I joined @naakbars b/c they hunted me down and forced me to sit still long enough to tell me about their sustainability goals. They’re doing everything they can to acknowledge their climate impacts and find solutions. I’ve been really impressed to their commitment to sustainability, b/c that’s especially hard when your product is food. They’re a small company run by passionate people who want to make the world better through sport. I’m excited for the next years with them!

Took a dawn lap up Mt. Olympus with @nickmdanielson last week and he made me look so damn cool I knew I had to show the world. 

I spend most of my time indoors hunched over computers or math problems, but I’ve been getting out more and more to try to get fit for my upcoming races. Early season is always a little tough b/c I invariably try to ramp up too quickly. But steep climbs like Olympus are great for getting strong with less pounding than a road run, and they get me up in the mountains where I feel like my best. Very grateful to live in this amazing place and have such a strong body to do these things. 

This shoot was part of a short film we’re (well, @trailboundsketches is) making for @nnormal_official about all the too-many things I try to do. I’m hoping they won’t glamorize the grind and will highlight some of the mental health issues I deal with, that I think I a lot of us deal with. Don’t let these sexy photos fool you. Life is good, but it’s hard too. It’s ok to be both.

A glimpse of our first adventure of the year!

Wanna join us for the rest of the season? It’ll be a ride!
Visit the link in bio to know more about our community.
#NNormal #YourPathNoTrace

🎥 @nickmdanielson

There was a presentation of elite runners for @transvulcaniabyutmb last night. I stood on a stage and looked at a crowd of people with ideas,stories, potential I could never dream of. They stood below and clapped for me. I told myself I belonged there. 

We so often celebrate people like me, but how many intelligent, interesting, worthwhile people are passed by while I enjoy my charmed life? I train hard, but certainly not harder than so many other people who don’t win races. For whatever physiological or socioeconomic reasons, my hard work goes further. It’s not because I’m better, I’m more fortunate. 

You can see much of the race route from the town I’m staying in. I looked at it today and thought about what might happen tomorrow. Maybe I’ll have an amazing race and be a legend. Maybe I’ll blow up and drop out after 10km. I am going to try so hard and what a gift it is to be young and strong and to have this opportunity to test myself among the best in this stunning place. In not so long a time I’ll be the one in the crowd looking up at the new young strong people winning races, and what will it all have meant?

If I don’t celebrate and protect this sport and its people and landscapes the same way you’ve all celebrated and protected me, then it won’t mean anything. But if we look beyond the competition at what really makes these experiences special, then I think we can change the world for the better. So, most of the time, I sit at my desk and try to do good for us with @footprintsrunning and @nnormal_official and @naakbars and @protectourwintwers . It’s fun to break the routine and go on a cool trip for a cool run. 

But of course I WOULD say that, just in case I blow up again. See you out there!

We did it! What an amazing day in La Palma at @transvulcaniabyutmb . My race strategy is always to go 5% or 10% harder than I know I’m capable of and see if I can hang on. And my goodness it took everything I had but today it worked out. It was a serious mental effort from start to finish. But the views of the island and the full moon and the volcano and the ocean and so many other things were incredible. I kept thinking about how much this island has suffered from the volcano recently, and it made me want to work harder. They all seem to know me here, and it means a lot. 

Thanks to so many people and organizations who support me in this crazy sport. Thanks to @nnormal_official for the best equipment and @naakbars for keeping me fueled through training and these big efforts. And thanks to all of you for following along! Feeling very grateful tonight. 

Great photo from @kirsten.kortebein

Yes, Dakota, today we celebrate people like you. While running is just joy and your platform to share your beliefs, we admire your committment, effort, and will to run for something bigger than yourself.

11 years after your first win at @transvulcaniabyutmb, you did it again! 🤯🎩
#NNormal #YourPathNoTrace

📹 @nickmdanielson

Creo que lo he dicho muchas veces, también se lo he dicho a él en persona siempre que he tenido oportunidad desde que nos conocimos en 2012, precisamente en La Palma: ¡Qué suerte tengo de tenerte como amigo!
En un momento muy difícil para mí y para mi familia en el año 2017, Dakota estuvo ahí, casi a los pies de la cama.
Hemos recorrido muchos lugares de España juntos: Picos de Europa, Mallorca, Zegama, Valladolid…
Siempre, hayan pasado 1 o 5 años, me siento a su lado como si hubiéramos estado juntos el pasado fin de semana. 
Por eso y por muchas cosas más me alegro muchísimo de su victoria en Transvulcania, una de sus carreras favoritas y en su isla más querida y con un pueblo que lo adora. 
¡Felicidades, AMIGO!

📷 @vanmarty • #transvulcania #transvulcaniabyutmb #lapalma #islascanarias #islabonita #trailrunning #deparunner

Well I just got home from Spain and I’m feeling so grateful for a great trip. After 10+ years of traveling there periodically for racing, I’ve made some really important friends. And this has only accelerated working with @nnormal_official in Mallorca. I think my success in racing is partly the result of feeling supported by so many people locally. 

The carbon impact of a trip like this weighs on my mind heavily. But I’ve come to believe it’s often better to bring people together than to reduce individual impacts. The connection between climate problems and climate solutions is people, and focusing on individual impacts drives us apart. But coming together brings out the best in us and gives us the ability to work together on things like advancing transportation options that don’t ruin the environment. My wonderful friends abroad remind me that we’re stronger together than apart. 

Anyway, that’s a little sappy, but hey, so am I. Thanks for all the support everyone!
@naakbars

A new episode of The Everyday Ultra Podcast featuring Dakota Jones is now available!

Known as one of the best mountain runners in the sport, Dakota Jones is a professional trail runner for NNormal based out of the Salt Lake City area. Over his career, he has notched up incredible results such as a podiums at Hardrock 100, wins at Javelina Jundred, Canyons 50K, and Broken Arrow, and tons of other races. And most recently, he won the famous Transvulcania race, which was his second win at the prestigious event.

Outside of running, Dakota is focused on giving back to the planet, as he is the Executive Director of Footprints, which is a non-profit organization that is an incubator for climate change.

In this episode, Dakota breaks down his epic win at Transvulancia, how he’s evolved as an athlete over the years through self-awareness, and how he balances pressure and fun when it comes to racing. He also shares his epic plans to bike from Utah to Olympic Valley for Western States 100 in effort to raise money through Footprints to help support climate change activism.

Huge thank you for Dakota for coming on the show!

I’m biking to @wser 

If I had to choose between climate action and competition, I’d choose @footprintsrunning every time. But I don’t have to make that choice, b/c trail running brings us together in ways that make climate action more possible than we ever believed. 

I’m spending the next week riding to Lake Tahoe from Salt Lake City - 650 miles - to raise funds for my nonprofit Footprints. We want to fund a position supporting our campers with resources and campers after each camp, to ensure their climate projects are successful over the long term. I’d love for you to consider donating to this cause combining trail running with climate action. Follow the link in my bio to learn more. 

Thanks to @nnormal_official @patagonia_trailrunning @naakbars @1percentftp @protectourwinters for supporting these wild adventures. I have so much hope for the future. #runfootprints

I had this idea that biking across Nevada would be great heat training for @wser - instead, I’ve found the desert to be cool, rainy, and surprisingly alpine. This is the great basin and it’s defined by long, narrow mountain ranges - all of which I’m riding over - and huge open landscape. It’s beautiful. 

Thank you for your support of this fundraiser! We’re raising money for @footprintsrunning to support our work empowering climate action in the trail community. Please consider supporting us, there are prizes! Did you know I have 47 cards with me and I’ll send you one from the road if you give us $65 or more? See you out there!
#runfootprints

We did it! 

Last Thursday I left my house in Salt Lake City on my bike and yesterday I arrived at the start line of @wser in California! I took several roads, but mostly I took highway 50 in Nevada, and it was big and open and challenging and more beautiful than I could ever have imagined. 683 miles! Check out the daily routes on my strava. 

It’s a fundraiser for @footprintsrunning and so far we’ve raised over $5k of our $20k goal. The fundraiser continues until I cross the finish line of Western States. Every little bit counts, so please consider helping out today for climate action!

It was fun to be joined on the last days by @rabbitwolfcreative who are making a film about the trip. Stay tuned for more info on that!

Thanks to our amazing sponsors @patagonia_trailrunning @naakbars @protectourwinters for making all of this possible!

#runfootprints

Riding my bike to @wser was a luxury I could enjoy because I have a lot of privilege in my life. Running 100 miles is also a luxury - it’s proof that my basic needs are met to such a degree that I can expend huge amounts of energy doing something materially unnecessary. This trip was empowering and meaningful in a big way, but it was never meant to represent a literal solution to climate change. 

Climate action is not privileged white men doing hard physical things. It’s collective action for collective benefit, a succession of unsexy tasks that protect people and resources for the long term. It’s working with the government to create more and better public transit options; working with communities to incentivize more efficient energy production and use; working with bankers to move money out of fossil fuel investments. Climate action involves learning the history of redlining and discrimination that has caused people of color to be the hardest hit by climate impacts and then securing their basic needs and getting out of the way so they can lead us to a more equitable future. Climate action empowers and educates women everywhere. 

Climate action protects people most of all. The best solutions will give everyone the same privilege I had to have enough extra time and money and energy to enact a grand gesture for a larger purpose. That’s what we aim for at @footprintsrunning and that’s why this bike ride is a fundraiser for that organization. With your support, we can create a new conception of climate action in the outdoor industry, one project at a time.

Thank you for your incredible support so far: we’re nearly halfway to our fundraising goal and the project doesn’t end until I cross the Western States finish line sometime next Saturday evening. Thank you to our partners @protectourwinters @patagonia_trailrunning @naakbars for supporting our work. And thank you to @nnormal_official for supporting me in my endless quest to screw up my racing career for a larger purpose. With the right people by your side, anything is possible. 

#runfootprints 
📸 @evanperigo

In 2011 I dropped out of UTMB. The next afternoon I sat on a bench and watched @kilianjornet run by as he won the race. I told myself I’d come back one day soon. Well, I don’t know if 12 years later is soon, and I ran the 100km CCC rather than the full loop, but when I ran past that same bench while finishing my race last Friday, it still felt pretty full-circle. 

I tried so hard out there. I guess I’m the guy that goes fast from the start and takes risks now. I faded hard in the 2nd half but I never gave up and finishing 3rd is something I’ll always be proud of. @jonalbon and @shen.jiasheng were a full category better than me, and it was a close thing staying ahead of my fellow Americans @jonrea_sayray @drew_holmen and @sethruhling 

The cultural and environmental impact of the @utmbworldseries is highly concerning to me, but I can’t deny that the atmosphere at these races is incredible and the courses are spectacular. There’s something really special about competing against the best in the world. I hope to be able to work with the community to guide the organization onto a better path so we can fully enjoy this magnificent experience for many years to come. 

Thank you to my friends and family and incredible supporters: I truly couldn’t do this without you. Thanks to @nnormal_official and @naakbars for making the equipment that makes it all possible. Thanks @nickmdanielson for the great photos.

I’m proud to vote in our local elections here in Salt Lake City. I’m especially proud to support my sister @votemollyjones who is running to represent my district on the city council. If there’s anything I’ve learned about climate action, it’s that local politics can often have the biggest impacts. I hope you’re voting this month too!

Help us change how shoes are made! The @nnormal_official Kboix is our attempt to create a shoe that is truly modular, promoting sustainability through durability and repairability. It’s a truly modular shoe, which can be repaired by replacing only the parts that wear out, making it possible to use the same pair of shoes for any run in any place, and lasting years. 

We’re not done creating this - we need your help. We’re looking for runners to help us test this shoe before its release. You can help us find what works, fix what doesn’t, and be part of the development of a more sustainable shoe than ever before. Follow the link in my bio to get involved. 

One of the best parts of working with NNormal is their genuine commitment to sustainability. They’re the first to point out that this shoe isn’t perfect. But nothing is perfect, and this is an authentic effort to create something new that will dramatically improve the life cycle of shoes (and save you money in the process.) I hope you’ll join us! 

Thanks for the endless and diverse inspiration @kilianjornet - there truly is no one like you.
